Today, as most first days go, we learned what we need to do to make things better. Every year our bus schedules take a while to work out! If you‚Äôre wondering about time for lunch delivery, please have patience. Watch for the üöå this week and as we learn the route, the times will become more consistent. Deliveries will be between 10:30 and 1.

Also, if you signed up and do not receive a lunch or if you‚Äôd like to sign up, call Lisa Meers at 633.2375 between 8-4. We order food a week in advance and need to know numbers for planning. Our üöå routes may increase in deliveries and we appreciate your patience since this is a new way to serve lunch to thousands in our county. #il3

post_text: Wow! Our #SCPartners in education are helping our students and families during the pandemic! Thanks Farm Bureau! #il3
shared_text:
Kentucky Farm Bureau - Shelby County
August 21 at 6:35 PM ¬∑

By the end of next week (Aug. 26th) our parking lot at our Shelbyville Office (1201 Mt Eden Rd) will have FREE WIFI for those without Internet needing it for school work. Our Great Organization- Kentucky Farm Bureau is ‚ÄúBig on Commitment" to our Citizens and "Big on Education‚Äù. KFB is offering this at no cost to anyone who needs it as it recognizes the strain this pandemic has put on working families and children displaced from their classrooms. Those needing WIFI, may pull up into the parking lot and download school work from 7:00 am to 10:00pm everyday. The hot spot will be named KFBFreeWIFI. Enjoy and strive to get all A‚Äôs!
(Simpsonville Office will be available for the same in the coming weeks)

post_text:
While Shelby County Public Schools is navigating a challenging start to a new school year, we have teachers and administrators who are ready to meet their students and begin a successful school year. They are up to the challenge. Teachers are in trainings from August 10th - 25th planning and preparing for students whether it is online, through paper and pencil resources, or in-person! One teacher tweeted from a training this morning, "we are not 'crisis teaching' anymore...teaching & learning WILL HAPPEN this fall in Shelby County Public Schools. Teachers are spaced 6 feet apart at the training and can remove masks. The rule is "Mask when you Move." Some teachers are attending virtually.

Follow our hashtag on twitter #SCFall2020 to see the inspirational winning attitudes of our staff! #IL3 #SCThinksBigger

shared_text:
Tolya Ellis is with Alton Lee Webb and Rachel Watts Webb.
August 6 at 11:43 PM ¬∑

Yesterday @ PSE was our first official PD and what powerful words these two (Rachel & Lee Webb) brought to the forefront.

1. Empathy vs. Compassion = Shifting one‚Äôs mindset from emotional drain & strain to one of emotional gain.

2. Understanding vs. Wisdom = Do I just get ‚Äúit‚Äù or do I get ‚Äúit‚Äù and put ‚Äúit‚Äù into action?

3. Self-care is not selfish = Focusing my lens on what is important to me, why it is important, and how will I implement ‚Äúit‚Äù in my life everyday?

GOD BLESS both of you and your family! üôèüèΩüíØ‚ù§Ô∏è

post_text:
Dual Credit Students/Families:

If you have received a bill from JCTC recently, it is likely for digital content/online content associated with dual credit courses. The digital content/online content charges are the financial responsibility of the student. Unfortunately, we do not know in advance what those are going to be for each class. Here are directions for making payment online if you need them.

Spring semester tuition charges have been paid by SCPS/KHEAA. If your student has exceeded the allotted number of paid courses, took more than two courses in one semester, or did not earn a passing grade in a dual credit course there may also be tuition charges on your itemized JCTC bill. In these situations, the tuition is the financial responsibility of the student.

Please let me know if you have any further questions,

Susanne M. Burkhardt
SCPS College and Career Coordinator
susanne.burkhardt@shelby.kyschools.us

At the July 9th meeting, our Board of Education voted to amend the school calendar. Students will begin school on August 26th. Parents should check emails around 5:00 pm on Friday, July 10th for information regarding the re-opening of schools and a school specific survey to complete. Those unable to access email and the online survey can pick up information at the schools after 5:00 pm on Friday. Thank you for your patience as we plan for safety and instruction for our our students and staff.

Dr. Sally Sugg, superintendent, issued a video message tonight along with Nate Jebsen, MLCHS principal.

https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=tQPBxB0xVaM&feature=youtu.be

2019-2020
Courier Journal Sports Awards

Girls Special Olympics
Athlete of the Year
Emme Harrod,
Martha Layne Collins:
Harrod's competitive spirit has led her to participate in a wide variety of sports. She has been active with various Special Olympic teams in the Louisville area depending upon which sports were available. Harrod has participated in cheerleading, basketball, soccer, track and field, swimming and bowling. Her athleticism has won her several first place finishes in swimming at the state level. In addition to Special Olympics, Harrod is also a member of the Unified Basketball team at Martha Layne Collins High School. This past fall she scored one of the two touchdowns for her class in the Junior-Senior Powder Puff football game. The joy on her face and the hugs from her classmates was wonderful to see!

Students asked questions and made suggestions for future books the author may pen! #IL3

post_text:
This morning, Dr. Neihof, Superintendent of SCPS, was shocked when his admin team didn't log on for their regularly scheduled 9:00 am meeting. SCPS principals and staff were waiting on the front lawn of Central Office to applaud their retiring superintendent. Teachers and staff also arranged a parade with decorated cars, honking, waves, and well-wishes. Dr. Neihof officially retires on June 30th.
He has inspired us all to learn, to lead, and to live and has challenged Shelby County to "Think Big!"

After the parade, the staff logged into Zoom:)

post_text: With questions about the upcoming school year and COVID-19, Shelby County Public Schools has convened a task force for the purpose of planning for the 2020-2021 school year. It is comprised of parents, students, teachers, classified staff, health officials, board representative, and school administrators. The task force met Wednesday, June 10th, and will reconvene. Their first task is to create and push out a survey to SCPS families and staff. The survey will be pushed out by June 19th. Decisions about the 2020-2021 school year will be made with the input from the surveys and with guidelines set by the CDC, KDE, and local, state, and federal guidelines.

Check out this video for information: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xj5lewzNxU4

All Summer Reading registration, Grab-and-Go activity kit request forms, and FAQ are on the SC Public Library's website: https://scplibrary.net/summer-reading.

If you have questions, please call the Shelby County Public Library Youth Librarian, Megan Langlois at meganl@scplibrary.net or 633.3803.

post_text: After Spring Break, teachers and staff recomposed their NTI/SnoGo lesson focus to project based learning and student led opportunities. In this video, you see a zoom meeting in progress with a student seminar led by Nash, a student in Ms. Seely's 2nd/3rd grade class at Painted Stone Elementary. He was doing a demonstration on "How to Make Scrambled Eggs!" The seminar was a success and there should be plenty of parents having breakfast in bed tomorrow thanks to Nash! This type of lesson opportunity fits our Profile of a Graduate and our Strategic Leadership Plan in SCPS. Want to learn more about our PoG -- visit www.shelby.kyschools.us! #IL3 #SCThinksBigger #HealthyatHome #TeamKentucky
